author: Vishal Rana

text:
Hi Toufiq, First of all thanks alot for explaining these concepts in such a lucid way. You are definitely one in a million guy who actually knew the things and can teach those to others. Thanks man!

I do also have a query regarding last_value() function. I wanted to show to you that using first_value() function and ordering results in ascending manner alone, we can replace the need to use the last_value() function altogether. I did this and got the result which you obtained using last_value() function and modified frame clause. Do let me know in case I am missing some catch in my approach or I may face an error in future for finding least priced product. Attaching my sql script here. 

select *,
first_value(product_name) over(partition by product_category order by price desc) as most_exp_product,
first_value(product_name) over(partition by product_category order by price asc) as least_exp_product
from product;

text:
First value is not impacted because of the default frame clause which SQL uses (RANGE BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW).
This mean, all window functions will have access to the very first record of the partition always.

And since FIRST_VALUE always looks for the data in first record of the partition, we dont really need to specify a different frame clause since the default frame clause will always have the first record of partition.

Hope this clarifies.

Thanks a lot for this video, very straight forward explanations. From my observation in CASE statement we can refer directly to lag() column. Below is an SQL code which works for me (refer to 23:28 timeframe in the video) 
select e.*,
lag(salary) over(partition by dept_name order by emp_id) as prev_emp_salary,
case 
when salary < prev_emp_salary then 'lower'
when salary > prev_emp_salary then 'higher'
when salary = prev_emp_salary then 'equal'
end as sal_range
from employee as e;

text:
Inside over clause, you need to order by salary in descending order so you get the records with highest salary on top..

Also you cannot use max(salary) without a group by clause in this case so better remove it..

Modify query as below:

select * 
from (select e.*, 
  row_number() over (partition by dept_name order by salary desc) as rn
 from employee e) x
where x.rn < 4;
